<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910903-0060</DOCNO><DOCID>910903-0060.</DOCID><HL>   Ex-Real Estate Chief   Convicted of Fraud,   Sentenced to Prison</HL><DATE>09/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   ASB</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)FLORIDA (FL)ILLINOIS (IL)NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   PHILADELPHIA -- A Miami hotelier was sentenced to 24 yearsin prison for defrauding a large failed California thrift anda Miami real estate company of $2.2 million in the mid-1980s.   Leonard Pelullo, one-time chief executive of now-defunctreal estate company Royale Group Ltd., was convicted of 49counts of wire fraud and one count under the federalRacketeering Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law in U.S.District Court here. Mr. Pelullo agreed to pay restitution of$8.8 million in fines, racketeering forfeitures andrestitution, federal prosecutors said.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Pelullo was convicted of diverting $2.1 million inloans from American Savings andamp; Loan Association for personaluse by overstating his costs in renovating six Miami artdeco-style hotels. It was also alleged that he fraudulentlyobtained money from Royale to repay a debt to Philadelphiaorganized-crime figures. American Savings andamp; Loan was acquiredby investor Robert Bass after it failed in 1988; it nowoperates as American Savings Bank.   In a sentencing recommendation, prosecutors also notedindependent investigations into Mr. Pelullo's other businessactivities being conducted in New Jersey, California, Floridaand Illinois. In all four cases, he allegedly bilkedcompanies he had acquired or controlled, in some cases bycharging bogus &quot;consulting fees&quot; arranged by shell companies,prosecutors said.   Attorneys for Mr. Pelullo couldn't be reached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>